I’d merge them into one headless shell component, with two built-in slot components for content:

## 1. Interface signature

```ts
type CashflowTablePeriodCellTone = "balance" | "final" | "neutral"; 
// "neutral" = current "none"

type CashflowTablePeriodCellAmountSlotProps = {
  progressPercentage?: number;
};

type CashflowTablePeriodCellSummarySlotProps = {
  currency: string;
  balanceQuality?: BalanceQuality | null;
};

type CashflowTablePeriodCellBaseProps = {
  columnIndex: number;
  dateFrom: string;
  value: number | null; // shared shell state, used for semantic coloring
  tone?: CashflowTablePeriodCellTone;
  isBold?: boolean;
  onClick?: () => void;
};

type CashflowTablePeriodCellProps =
  | (CashflowTablePeriodCellBaseProps & {
      kind: "amount";
      value: number;
      children: React.ReactElement<CashflowTablePeriodCellAmountSlotProps>;
    })
  | (CashflowTablePeriodCellBaseProps & {
      kind: "summary";
      children: React.ReactElement<CashflowTablePeriodCellSummarySlotProps>;
    });

declare const CashflowTablePeriodCell: React.MemoExoticComponent<
  (props: CashflowTablePeriodCellProps) => JSX.Element
> & {
  Amount: React.MemoExoticComponent<
    (props: CashflowTablePeriodCellAmountSlotProps) => JSX.Element
  >;
  Summary: React.MemoExoticComponent<
    (props: CashflowTablePeriodCellSummarySlotProps) => JSX.Element
  >;
};
```

## 2. Usage example

```tsx
// Net balance row
<CashflowTablePeriodCell
  kind="amount"
  columnIndex={index}
  dateFrom={period.dateFrom}
  value={period.netBalance}
  tone="balance"
  isBold
>
  <CashflowTablePeriodCell.Amount
    progressPercentage={period.progressPercentage}
  />
</CashflowTablePeriodCell>

// Category data row with custom click
<CashflowTablePeriodCell
  kind="amount"
  columnIndex={index}
  dateFrom={period.dateFrom}
  value={value}
  tone="neutral"
  onClick={() => openDetail(index)}
>
  <CashflowTablePeriodCell.Amount />
</CashflowTablePeriodCell>

// Final balance row
<CashflowTablePeriodCell
  kind="summary"
  columnIndex={index}
  dateFrom={period.dateFrom}
  value={period.finalBalance?.value ?? null}
  tone="final"
  isBold
>
  <CashflowTablePeriodCell.Summary
    currency={currency}
    balanceQuality={period.finalBalance?.balanceQuality ?? null}
  />
</CashflowTablePeriodCell>

// Income / costs totals
<CashflowTablePeriodCell
  kind="summary"
  columnIndex={index}
  dateFrom={period.dateFrom}
  value={period.income}
  tone="neutral"
  isBold
>
  <CashflowTablePeriodCell.Summary currency={currency} />
</CashflowTablePeriodCell>
```

## 3. What this design hides internally

The caller never sees:

- `useIsColumnSelected(columnIndex)` and the optimized selection-store logic
- the default click fallback: `setPeriod(dayjs(dateFrom))`
- `TableCell` styling details:
  - borders
  - highlight border colors
  - background
  - pointer cursor
  - right alignment
  - `aria-selected`
- the semantic color mapping for balance/final/neutral
- formatting details:
  - `formatCashflowAmount`
  - `CurrencyAmount`
  - `CashflowQualityIndicator`
  - `LinearProgress`
- memoization strategy and render optimization details

## 4. Trade-offs of this approach

**Pros**
- Clear separation: the shell owns behavior, the slot owns presentation
- Narrow API surface; no giant prop matrix
- Fits the actual current use cases very well
- Easy to keep memoized and performance-conscious
- Current components can be migrated incrementally as thin wrappers

**Cons**
- Slightly more JSX nesting than a single flat component
- Two concepts to learn: shell + slot
- If a third visual variant appears, you’ll likely add a third slot component
- It is a bit less “one-shot” than a monolithic prop bag

